  "eprint": {
    "title": "Designing Reverse Firewalls for the Real World",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Angèle Bossuat",
        "email": "bossuat@irisa",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Xavier Bultel",
        "email": "bultel@insa-cvl",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Pierre-Alain Fouque",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Cristina Onete",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Thyla van der Merwe",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "Reverse Firewalls (RFs) were introduced by Mironov and\nStephens-Davidowitz to address algorithm-substitution attacks (ASAs)\nin which an adversary subverts the implementation of a provably-secure\ncryptographic primitive to make it insecure. This concept was applied\nby Dodis et al. in the context of secure key exchange (handshake phase),\nwhere the adversary wants to exfiltrate sensitive information by using\na subverted client implementation. RFs are used as a means of \"sanitizing\"\nthe client-side protocol in order to prevent this exfiltration. In\nthis paper, we propose a new security model for both the handshake and\nrecord layers, a.k.a. secure channel. We present a signed, Diffie-Hellman\nbased secure channel protocol, and show how to design a provably-secure\nreverse firewall for it. Our model is stronger since the adversary has a\nlarger surface of attacks, which makes the construction challenging. Our\nconstruction uses classical and off-the-shelf cryptography.",
    "keywords": [
      "reverse firewalls",
      "provable security"
    ],
    "category": "Cryptographic protocols",
    "publication_info": "Published elsewhere. Minor revision. ESORICS 2020",
    "last_updated": "2020-07-12",
